# 5. Demonstration I: f49v — HERBAL/PROCESS grammatical key

## 5.1 Regime

HERBAL/PROCESS reading key: vertical operator grammar beside running corpus text.

## 5.2 Why this folio comes first

f49v should open the translation demonstration because it explains how the parser is to be used on ordinary herbal/process pages. It is not treated as a normal recipe page. It is treated as an internal grammatical key: a vertical sequence of operator labels placed beside ordinary manuscript text.

The function of the page is therefore practical. It appears to remind an initiated reader how to read compact tokens in this regime: preparation/variant, process field, output/relation, closure, active frame, stabilization, regulation, procedure-initiation, and transformation.

This makes f49v the natural bridge between the parser paper and the first normal herbal-page translation.

## 5.3 Visual and layout context

The page combines four elements that should be read together:

```text
1. ordinary running text;
2. a left-side vertical numbered/operator column;
3. a large herbal/process diagram;
4. a small star/index marker near the top of the visual structure.
```

The large plant-like figure is not treated as botanical decoration alone. Under the present model it functions as a vertical process diagram: root/base at the bottom, carrier/stem rising upward, branching conduits, large green carrier/leaf fields, white openings or channels, and a small star-like marker as an index or class sign. The visual field therefore supports the idea that the page is teaching how text, diagram, and operator grammar work together.

The left-side column is especially important because it stands apart from normal running text. It behaves like a grammatical guide or crib-sheet rather than a normal prose line. The nearby numbers and the repeated y-closures make it plausible that the column is meant to be read as a sequence of operator examples.

## 5.4 Transcription status of the vertical column

The vertical column is not completely uniform across modern transcriptions. Individual glyph readings differ in a few places. In particular, Stolfi/Zandbergen-style readings do not always agree on whether a glyph should be read as `e`, `ch`, `s`, `p`, or another close form in the column.

This uncertainty must be recorded explicitly. The present reading does not silently normalize the column. It uses the following rule:

```text
A vertical-column glyph may be preferred when:
1. it fits the visible glyph form;
2. it fits the local vertical sequence;
3. it fits an already established operator value;
4. it completes one of the five closure-delimited chains;
5. it does not require changing the operator meaning ad hoc.
```

Thus, the page is not used as a free source for inventing new meanings. It is used as a confirmation environment for meanings already derived from the corpus-level parser.

