# 10. Transcription errors, witness variation, and correction rules

This demonstration does not freely correct the text. Corrections are allowed only under explicit rules.

## 10.1 Locked correction rule

```text
The parser may flag structurally suspicious places.
It may not correct them merely to fit the model.
Correction requires independent visual, witness, or local graphical confirmation.
```

## 10.2 Permitted correction classes

```text
POSSIBLE_E_I_TRANSCRIPTION_AMBIGUITY
OPEN_A_TERMINAL_FLAG
MISSING_INITIAL_CLOSURE_GLYPH
PARSER_GUIDED_VISUAL_CORRECTION
WITNESS_REPLACED
SHORT_LABEL
H_STACK / repeated activation validation
FREE_H_PAIR_REMAINDER
NON_C_EMBEDDED_H_EXCEPTION
```

## 10.3 What counts as evidence for correction

A correction may be proposed only when at least one of the following applies:

1. another witness preserves a more coherent or visually plausible reading;
2. the glyph shape visibly supports the correction;
3. the local graphical environment supports the reading independently;
4. the correction resolves a known ambiguity class such as e/i or r/k;
5. the uncorrected form is structurally isolated while the corrected form fits an independently established pattern.

## 10.4 What is not allowed

The following are not allowed:

1. changing a glyph because the preferred meaning would be more convenient;
2. changing operator values inside a token to force a translation;
3. treating every ambiguous form as confirmation;
4. silently normalizing witness disagreement;
5. using the visual image as the only justification for a textual correction.

## 10.5 Example: f76r r/k ambiguity

At f76r.L.24, H/F/V/U read r while C reads k. The preferred reading is r, but the ambiguity must be recorded.

```text
f76r.L.24 = r in H/F/V/U; k in C
preferred = r
status = witness ambiguity / possible graphic confusion
```

This matters because k would mark stabilization, while r marks output/relation. The majority reading and the position after local carrier + stabilization favor r.

