# 11. Why this is a direct demonstration rather than a new theory

This document does not introduce new operator meanings. It applies the existing parser to selected folios. The same values are used across PROCESS, SPECIAL/ASTRO, ASTRO, and BALNEO contexts.

The evidential force is combinatorial. The model must be correct not only in isolated sign meanings, but also in sign order, positional behavior, key-page regime, visual correspondence, and semantic coherence across running text. A free-association model would have to explain why the same inventory repeatedly produces coherent readings across different key-page types and visual regimes.

---

# 12. Provisional conclusion

This side paper is not a new parser. It demonstrates how the established parser is used for translation.

The selected demonstrations should therefore balance explanation and application: one key page to show the internal reading aid, and several ordinary or recipe-like pages to show that the parser works as a direct reading system. A normal herbal folio, a balneo folio, a pharma/vessel folio, and a final compressed star/text folio together provide a stronger demonstration than key pages alone.

The strongest conservative conclusion is that the manuscript contains both internal reading aids and applied recipe/procedure pages. The key pages show how an initiated reader should apply the grammar. The ordinary pages show the grammar in use. The final text-heavy pages may represent the most compressed form of the notation: minimal visual support, maximum structural encoding.

The demonstration therefore supports the central claim of the main paper: Voynichese is complete at the structural-functional level, while remaining incomplete or refinable at the historical-lexical level.



f49v — Structural-Functional Translation and Image Analysis
1. Page function

f49v is treated as a HERBAL/PROCESS grammatical key page, not as an ordinary recipe page.

The page combines:

ordinary running text,
a left vertical numbered/operator column,
a large plant-shaped process diagram,
a small star/index marker above the plant form.

Under the structural-functional parser, this page functions as an internal reading aid. It does not give ordinary word meanings. It shows how the operator grammar should be applied in this regime: field, output, closure, activation, stabilization, regulation, procedure-initiation, and transformation. This is consistent with the existing f49v interpretation as five y-closed operator demonstrations.

2. Visual analysis

The illustration is not read primarily as botanical realism. It is read as a vertical process diagram.

2.1 Root / base

The lower structure is a rounded root/base mass filled with repeated small curved marks.

Structural reading:

root/base mass
= terminal base / residue / stored material matrix

Functional interpretation:

The process begins or terminates in a base/residue/mass field.
The many small marks indicate discrete particles, units, granules, or distributed material points.

This fits the wider visual grammar where brown/root/base structures correspond to terminal mass, residue, base, conduit, or material matrix, and dots/circles correspond to discrete fractions or particles.

2.2 Stem / carrier

A long green stem rises from the base into the upper plant body.

Structural reading:

vertical stem
= carrier path / conduit / local process channel

Functional interpretation:

The material or process-state is carried upward from the base into a higher processing field.

The stem is therefore not simply botanical. It is a carrier-route between base material and upper processing/output fields.

2.3 Upper green fields

The large green paired leaf-like structures dominate the upper diagram.

Structural reading:

green fields
= carrier matrix / local process fields / treated material zones

Functional interpretation:

The upper part of the diagram shows expanded process fields where material is held, distributed, opened, or transformed.

The two large side-fields are not identical decorative leaves. They behave like paired process chambers or carrier fields.

2.4 White internal openings

The white curved areas inside the green structures are important.

Structural reading:

white openings
= apertures / channels / collectors / cleared passage zones

Functional interpretation:

The green carrier fields contain openings or channels through which material, flow, or output can be separated or directed.

This supports the interpretation of the upper plant form as a diagrammatic process structure rather than a natural plant.

2.5 Central flower / output head

At the top center, a pale/white central form rises above the branching stem system.

Structural reading:

central upper head
= collector / output zone / final process field

Functional interpretation:

Material carried upward through the stem and branches is organized toward an upper output or collector field.
2.6 Small star marker

A small blue star-like sign appears near the upper right.

Structural reading:

star
= process label / class marker / index marker

Functional interpretation:

The star marks the page or diagram as belonging to a specific process class, component class, or indexed operator category.

This is important because the manuscript later uses star-like markers in more compressed text/index contexts. On f49v, the star may already function as a small classifier or index sign attached to the process diagram.

